Crime Master Putin
Moscow – Medical experts from Germany, France, and Sweden agreed that Alexei Navalny was a victim of the nerve agent Novichok. Navalny is Russia's president Putin's foremost opponent and the founder of an anti-corruption foundation.
Fortunately, due to Navalny's survival, relations between Russia and Germany did not deteriorate further.
To demonstrate her "clear stance," German Chancellor Merkel announced that Navalny is a "victim persecuted for his advocacy of freedom of speech."
In her view, the incident was very serious and could only be responded to by the Russian government.
She emphasized that the whole world needed an explanation.
Merkel called on Russian authorities to conduct an independent and transparent investigation.
The EU and the UK also supported this call.
If the investigation proves that the Russian government was behind the incident, the EU Commission will impose new sanctions.
Regardless, according to the Chemical Weapons Convention, poisoning is prohibited.
This is not the first time the Putin government has used the nerve agent Novichok against its political opponents.
In 2018, Russian former double agent Sergei Skripal and his daughter Yulia were poisoned on British soil.
Both survived and went into hiding.
The Kremlin strongly denies both incidents.
Regarding the Navalny incident, Kremlin spokesman Dmitry Peskov insisted there was "no evidence to blame the Russian government."
Sergei Naryshkin, the director of Russia's Foreign Intelligence Service, even said it was an act by Western intelligence agencies to implicate the Russian government.
Naryshkin's statement is clearly unreasonable, but he also points out a fact: the Navalny incident is more detrimental than beneficial to Russia.
Poisoning a prominent political opponent just before the upcoming election, using a poison developed by the former Soviet Union, is unfathomable.
Especially given the protests by the people of neighboring Belarus against the August elections, this timing is particularly telling.
Moreover, the Kremlin's initial reaction to the Navalny incident was particularly puzzling.
Shouldn't the Russian government have planned more carefully before carrying out the crime?
If, as Germany claims, it was indeed carried out by the Russian government, this assassination would also be a failed operation.
Putin has long been the Darth Vader of international politics, intervening in the US election, inciting street protests in France, pushing for Brexit in the UK, and supporting Syria's Bashar al-Assad.
As a former KGB officer, he is shrewd, farsighted, and cunning.
Why couldn't he kill Sergei Skripal and Alexei Navalny?
Why could Navalny escape to Germany and be quickly diagnosed as having been poisoned?
Now, Putin faces international condemnation and sanctions, with the Nord Stream 2 gas pipeline project to Germany under threat of cancellation.
This assassination clearly wasn't worth it.
In fact, this further stoked public opposition to the Russian authorities' atrocities.
Even if it wasn't Putin who did it, blaming Western intelligence agencies would be even more excessive.
If such accusations were true, scientists from Germany and Sweden would not have revealed the truth about the nerve agent Novichok.
More likely, it comes from a political conspiracy orchestrated by Putin's inner circle.
Perhaps Putin needed Navalny to silence him before the election, or perhaps it was due to Navalny's anti-corruption investigations.
In Russia, you can buy various products and services on the black market, including military-grade nerve agents.
Putin's political enforcers, though loyal, are quite foolish; they thought poisoning Navalny was a good idea, with only a few knowing the truth.
Other failed poisoning attempts shared similar characteristics: the poisoning of journalists Vladimir Kara-Murza in 2015 and 2017. Kara-Murza was the coordinator of the Khodorkovsky Public Investigation Committee.
Poisoning of Mediazona publisher Peter Verzhbitsky in 2018.
Mediazona is a website reporting on Russian judicial abuses.
Further back, there was the poisoning of Alexander Litvinenko, a former FSB officer, in 2006. Alexander Litvinenko frequently criticized Russia's security agencies.
Such poisoning, like the Navalny incident, often backfires.
In 2004, Anna Politkovskaya, a columnist for the liberal newspaper Novaya Gazeta, was poisoned on a flight from Moscow to Beslan, though she survived; two years later, she was shot dead in the elevator of her apartment building.
As Putin said, her death dealt a significant blow to the image of the Russian government.
This is not to exonerate the Kremlin in any way.
No matter whether Putin personally ordered it, the system he created allowed such crimes to occur. Such a system is both ineffective and pointless, merely a farce involving shameless performers.
The death of Navalny is what the Kremlin wants, and making their master Putin pleased is the ultimate goal of the hounds.
Loyalty is the sole goal in Putin's inner circle.
Even if the poisoning fails, they will not face punishment.
Because they are doing this for the president's benefit.
Those seeking proof of the poisoning may be disappointed.
No matter what, the Kremlin remains the mastermind.
Western countries must clearly state that they will impose sanctions on Russia even if their own economies are affected.
Putin created a system centered around himself.
All responsibilities in Russia are attributed to him.
